          "body": "Verses 3-4 are the psalm's dramatic center of gravity, narrated from the safe distance of rescue. 'The cords of death encompassed me and the terrors of Sheol came upon me; I found distress and sorrow' (116:3). The imagery is hunting imagery: cords (*chevel*) as snares, death as a trapper. Sheol's 'terrors' (*metsar*) are the crushing, narrowing straits of the underworld's approach. Whether the crisis was physical illness, mortal danger, persecution, or near-death in battle, the psalmist refuses to soften it. Three nouns pile up: anguish, trouble, sorrow. Then, at the bottom of the pit, a single sentence of prayer: 'O LORD, I beseech You, save my life' (116:4). Five Hebrew words. The name of the LORD invoked; a particle of urgent entreaty (*anna*); a single verb of rescue (*malat* — to deliver, to slip away). The simplicity of the prayer is pastoral instruction: there is no elaborate rhetoric required. The bottom of the pit needs only the name and the verb."
